\begin_body

\begin_layout Section
Notes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a Plummer model (Dejonghe, H.1987, MNRAS 224, 13) with potential
 with units 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{s}$
\end_inset

 the Plummer scale radius (which sets the size of the cluster core), 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 the total mass of the cluster and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\tau}$
\end_inset

 some unit time.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{s}$
\end_inset

 be defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi_{s}=\frac{GM}{r_{s}},
\]

\end_inset

for the central potential
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi(r)=\frac{\psi_{s}}{\sqrt{1+r^{2}}}.
\]

\end_inset

Let use fix 
\begin_inset Formula $G=1\,r_{s}^{3}.M^{-1}.{\rm \bar{\tau}^{-2}}$
\end_inset

 in the new units so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{s}=1\,r_{s}^{2}\cdot\bar{\tau}^{-2}$
\end_inset

.
 This fixes the time unit 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\tau}$
\end_inset

, as we have the relation.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G=\tilde{G}{\rm m}^{3}.{\rm kg}^{-1}.{\rm s^{-2}}=\tilde{G}\frac{{\rm m}^{3}}{r_{s}^{3}}\frac{{\rm kg}^{-1}}{M^{-1}}\frac{s^{-2}}{\bar{\tau}{}^{-2}}r_{s}^{3}.M_{\odot}^{-1}.{\rm \tau^{-2}}=\bar{G}r_{s}^{3}.M^{-1}.{\rm \bar{\tau}^{-2}},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{G}=6.67430\times10^{-11}$
\end_inset

.
 Consequently we can deduce from 
\begin_inset Formula $1=\tilde{G}\frac{{\rm m}^{3}}{r_{s}^{3}}\frac{M}{{\rm kg}}\frac{\bar{\tau}^{2}}{s^{2}}$
\end_inset

 that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\bar{\tau}}{s}=\sqrt{\frac{1}{\tilde{G}}\frac{r_{s}^{3}}{{\rm m}^{3}}\frac{{\rm kg}}{M}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, in those units the potential (per unit mass) is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi(r)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+r^{2}}}.
\]

\end_inset

We use those units from now on.
 For example, M3 has total mass 
\begin_inset Formula $M=4.5\cdot10^{5}M_{\odot}$
\end_inset

 and radius 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{s}=90\,{\rm ly}$
\end_inset

, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\tau}=1.0167\cdot10^{14}\,{\rm s}=3.2218\,{\rm Myr}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define, given a radius 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, the angular momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $L(v_{r},v_{t}|r)$
\end_inset

 and binding energy per unit mass 
\begin_inset Formula $E(v_{r},v_{t}|r)$
\end_inset

, functions of the radial velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{r}$
\end_inset

 and the tangential velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{t}\geq0$
\end_inset

 (defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}=\boldsymbol{v_{r}}+\boldsymbol{v_{t}}=v_{r}\hat{\boldsymbol{r}}+\boldsymbol{v_{t}}$
\end_inset

), as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E(v_{r},v_{t}|r)=\psi(r)-\frac{1}{2}v_{r}^{2}-\frac{1}{2}v_{t}^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L(v_{r},v_{t}|r)=rv_{t}
\]

\end_inset

which is a transformation with Jacobian 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
{\rm Jac}_{(v_{r},v_{t}|r)\rightarrow(E,L|r)}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\frac{\partial E}{\partial v_{r}} & \frac{\partial E}{\partial v_{t}}\\
\frac{\partial L}{v_{ar}} & \frac{\partial L}{\partial v_{t}}
\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
-v_{r} & -v_{t}\\
0 & r
\end{array}\right)\Rightarrow|{\rm Jac}|=r|v_{r}|
\]

\end_inset

To obtain a bijective transformation, we must chose wether to chose 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{r}\ge0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{r}\leq0$
\end_inset

.
 A priori, this choice might have an impact on the result, but we will should
 that the local and orbit-averaged diffusion coefficients are not that.
 The coordinate system is spherical, its origin being at the center of the
 globular cluster.
 Finally, we consider the corresponding anisotropic distribution functions
 of the field stars 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{q}(E,L|r)=F_{q}(E,L)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,L)$
\end_inset

-space.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,L)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(v_{r},v_{t})$
\end_inset

 are linked, we can make use of the following equalities (for the moment,
 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{r}$
\end_inset

 is determined modulo the sign)
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{q}(E,L|r)=f_{a}(v_{r}(E,L|r),v_{t}(E,L|r)|r)
\]

\end_inset

and its converse
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{a}(v_{r},v_{t}|r)=F_{q}(E(v_{r},v_{t}|r),L(v_{r},v_{t}|r))
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is an anisotropy parameter:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $q\in]0,2]$
\end_inset

: radially anisotropic
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $q=0$
\end_inset

: isotropic
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $q\in]-\infty,0[$
\end_inset

: tangentially anisotropic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the DF has spherical symmetry in position.
 Its expression is (for 
\begin_inset Formula $q\neq0$
\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{q}(E,L)=\frac{3\Gamma(6-q)}{2(2\pi)^{5/2}\Gamma(q/2)}E^{7/2-q}\mathbb{H}(0,\frac{q}{2},\frac{9}{2}-q,1;\frac{L^{2}}{2E})
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{H}(a,b,c,d;x)=\begin{cases}
\frac{\Gamma(a+b)}{\Gamma(c-a)\Gamma(a+d)}x^{a}._{2}F_{1}(a+b,1+a-c,a+d;x) & x\leq1\\
\frac{\Gamma(a+b)}{\Gamma(d-b)\Gamma(b+c)}x^{-b}._{2}F_{1}(a+b,1+b-d,b+c;\frac{1}{x}) & x\geq1
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

which reduces in the isotropic case 
\begin_inset Formula $(q=0)$
\end_inset

 to:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F(E)=\frac{3}{7\pi^{3}}(2E)^{7/2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Determination of the local diffusion coefficients
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The local diffusion coefficients are the average velocity changes per unit
 time.
 We are interested in computing 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle\Delta v_{||}\rangle(v_{r},v_{t}|r)=\frac{\langle\Delta v_{||}\rangle_{\delta t}}{\delta t}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle(\Delta v_{||})^{2}\rangle(v_{r},v_{t}|r)=\frac{\langle(\Delta v_{||})^{2}\rangle_{\delta t}}{\delta t}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle(\Delta v_{\perp})^{2}\rangle(v_{r},v_{t}|r)=\frac{\langle(\Delta v_{\perp})^{2}\rangle_{\delta t}}{\delta t}
\]

\end_inset

Consider a test star at position 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and initial velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}$
\end_inset

 which interacts with a field star with impact parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{a}$
\end_inset

 and velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}$
\end_inset

, Binney et Tremaine (2008, eq.
 (L.7) page 834) gives 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta v_{\perp}=\frac{2m_{a}V_{0}}{m+m_{a}}\frac{b/b_{90}}{1+b^{2}/b_{90}^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta v_{||}=\frac{2m_{a}V_{0}}{m+m_{a}}\frac{1}{1+b^{2}/b_{90}^{2}}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{V_{0}}=\boldsymbol{v}-\boldsymbol{v_{a}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{90}$
\end_inset

 is the 90Â° deflection radius, given by eq (L.8) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b_{90}=\frac{G(m+m_{a})}{V_{0}^{2}}
\]

\end_inset

Remember that in our units, 
\begin_inset Formula $G=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m,m_{a}$
\end_inset

 are given in fraction of the total mass 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 of the cluster.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, note that when considering a test star with energy and angular momentum
 (per unit mass) 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,L)$
\end_inset

, using the choise 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{r}\geq0$
\end_inset

 or the choice 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{r}\leq0$
\end_inset

 has an impact on the local change of velocity through 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We sum the effects of all the encounter up.
 Number density of field stars (at position 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

) within velocity space volume 
\begin_inset Formula ${\rm d}^{3}\boldsymbol{v_{a}}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{a}(\boldsymbol{v_{a}}|r){\rm d}^{3}\boldsymbol{v_{a}}$
\end_inset

 (remember that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{a}(\boldsymbol{v_{a}}|r)=f_{a}(v_{ar},v_{at}|r)$
\end_inset

).
 The number of encounters in a time 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta t$
\end_inset

 with impact parameters between 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b+{\rm d}b$
\end_inset

 is just this density times the volume of an annulus with inner radius 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, outer radius 
\begin_inset Formula $b+{\rm d}b$
\end_inset

, and length 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}\delta t$
\end_inset

, that is (eq.
 L9)
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
2\pi b{\rm d}bV_{0}\delta tf_{a}(\boldsymbol{v_{a}}|r){\rm d}^{3}\boldsymbol{v_{a}}
\]

\end_inset

We sum up over the velocities and the impact parameters.
 For the latter, we consider impact parameters between 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 and a cut-off 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

, traditionally given approximately by the radius of the subject star orbit.
 This yields
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle\Delta v_{\parallel}\rangle(r,\boldsymbol{v})=2\pi\int{\rm d}^{3}\boldsymbol{v_{a}}f_{a}(\boldsymbol{v_{a}}|r)\frac{m_{a}V_{0}^{2}b_{90}^{2}}{m+m_{a}}\ln(1+\Lambda^{2})
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle(\Delta v_{\parallel})^{2}\rangle(r,\boldsymbol{v})=2\pi\int{\rm d}^{3}\boldsymbol{v_{a}}f_{a}(\boldsymbol{v_{a}}|r)2V_{0}\left(\frac{m_{a}V_{0}b_{90}}{m+m_{a}}\right)^{2}\left(1-\frac{1}{1+\Lambda^{2}}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle(\Delta v_{\perp})^{2}\rangle(r,\boldsymbol{v})=2\pi\int{\rm d}^{3}\boldsymbol{v_{a}}f_{a}(\boldsymbol{v_{a}}|r)2V_{0}\left(\frac{m_{a}V_{0}b_{90}}{m+m_{a}}\right)^{2}\left(\ln(1+\Lambda^{2})+\frac{1}{1+\Lambda^{2}}-1\right)
\]

\end_inset

where we defined the Coulomb parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda=b_{{\rm max}}/b_{90}$
\end_inset

.
 Take 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda=\lambda N$
\end_inset

 (Binney et Tremaine, page 581) with 
\begin_inset Formula $N\sim10^{5}$
\end_inset

 for a globular cluster.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{V_{0}}=\boldsymbol{v}-\boldsymbol{v_{a}}$
\end_inset

.
 Since we assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 is large, we do not make any significant additional error by replacing
 the factor 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 by some typical stellar speed 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{{\rm typ}}$
\end_inset

, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Lambda=\frac{b_{{\rm max}}v_{{\rm typ}}^{2}}{G(m+m_{a})}.
\]

\end_inset

Doing all the replacement gives and applying the change of variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v'}=\boldsymbol{v}-\boldsymbol{v_{a}}=\boldsymbol{V_{0}}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle\Delta v_{\parallel}\rangle(r,\boldsymbol{v})=2\pi\ln(1+\Lambda^{2})G^{2}m_{a}(m_{a}+m)\int{\rm d}^{3}\boldsymbol{v'}\frac{f_{a}(\boldsymbol{v}-\boldsymbol{v'}|r)}{v'^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle(\Delta v_{\parallel})^{2}\rangle(r,\boldsymbol{v})=4\pi\left(1-\frac{1}{1+\Lambda^{2}}\right)G^{2}m_{a}^{2}\int{\rm d}^{3}\boldsymbol{v'}\frac{f_{a}(\boldsymbol{v}-\boldsymbol{v'}|r)}{v'}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle(\Delta v_{\perp})^{2}\rangle(r,\boldsymbol{v})=4\pi\left(\ln(1+\Lambda^{2})+\frac{1}{1+\Lambda^{2}}-1\right)G^{2}m_{a}^{2}\int{\rm d}^{3}\boldsymbol{v'}\frac{f_{a}(\boldsymbol{v}-\boldsymbol{v'}|r)}{v'}
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 is very large
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle\Delta v_{\parallel}\rangle(r,\boldsymbol{v})=4\pi\ln\Lambda G^{2}m_{a}(m_{a}+m)\int{\rm d}^{3}\boldsymbol{v'}\frac{f_{a}(\boldsymbol{v}-\boldsymbol{v'}|r)}{v'^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle(\Delta v_{\parallel})^{2}\rangle(r,\boldsymbol{v})=4\pi G^{2}m_{a}^{2}\int{\rm d}^{3}\boldsymbol{v'}\frac{f_{a}(\boldsymbol{v}-\boldsymbol{v'}|r)}{v'}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle(\Delta v_{\perp})^{2}\rangle(r,\boldsymbol{v})=4\pi(2\ln\Lambda-1)G^{2}m_{a}^{2}\int{\rm d}^{3}\boldsymbol{v'}\frac{f_{a}(\boldsymbol{v}-\boldsymbol{v'}|r)}{v'}
\]

\end_inset

Using spherical coordinates with axis 
\begin_inset Formula $(Oz)=\hat{\boldsymbol{r}}$
\end_inset

 the unit radius vector (parallel or antiparallel to the radial component
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}$
\end_inset

 by definition), we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle\Delta v_{\parallel}\rangle(r,\boldsymbol{v})=4\pi\ln\Lambda G^{2}m_{a}(m_{a}+m)\int_{0}^{\infty}{\rm d}v'\int_{0}^{\pi}{\rm d}\theta\sin\theta\int_{0}^{2\pi}{\rm d}\phi f_{a}(\boldsymbol{v}-\boldsymbol{v'}|r)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle(\Delta v_{\parallel})^{2}\rangle(r,\boldsymbol{v})=4\pi G^{2}m_{a}^{2}\int_{0}^{\infty}{\rm d}v'v'\int_{0}^{\pi}{\rm d}\theta\sin\theta\int_{0}^{2\pi}{\rm d}\phi f_{a}(\boldsymbol{v}-\boldsymbol{v'}|r)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle(\Delta v_{\perp})^{2}\rangle(r,\boldsymbol{v})=4\pi(2\ln\Lambda-1)G^{2}m_{a}^{2}\int_{0}^{\infty}{\rm d}v'v'\int_{0}^{\pi}{\rm d}\theta\sin\theta\int_{0}^{2\pi}{\rm d}\phi f_{a}(\boldsymbol{v}-\boldsymbol{v'}|r)
\]

\end_inset

where we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{a}(\boldsymbol{v}-\boldsymbol{v'}|r)=f_{a}(v_{ar},v_{at}|r)=F_{q}(E(v_{ar},v_{at}|r),L(v_{ar},v_{at}|r))
\]

\end_inset

with
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E(v_{ar},v_{at}|r)=\psi(r)-\frac{1}{2}v_{ar}{}^{2}-\frac{1}{2}v_{at}{}^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L(v_{ar},v_{at}|r)=rv_{at}
\]

\end_inset

For a given convention 
\begin_inset Formula $+$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $-$
\end_inset

 of the choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{r}$
\end_inset

, and given 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,L)$
\end_inset

 the parameters of the test star, obtain the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v_{+}}=(|v_{r}|,\boldsymbol{v_{t}})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v_{-}}=(-|v_{r}|,\boldsymbol{v_{t}})$
\end_inset

, which are symmetric with respect to the tangent plane where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v_{t}}$
\end_inset

 lives.
 In terms of spherical coordinates, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v_{+}}=(v,\theta_{0},0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v_{-}}=(v,\pi-\theta_{0},0)$
\end_inset

.
 Remember that the integration over the velocities 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v'}=\boldsymbol{v}-\boldsymbol{v_{a}}=\boldsymbol{V_{0}}$
\end_inset

of the field stars cover the whole 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{V_{0}}$
\end_inset

-space.
 Given a velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{V_{0}}$
\end_inset

 corresponds bijectively a field star velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v_{a}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We need to compute 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I_{1}(r,\boldsymbol{v})=\int_{0}^{\infty}{\rm d}v'\int_{0}^{\pi}{\rm d}\theta\sin\theta\int_{0}^{2\pi}{\rm d}\phi f_{a}(\boldsymbol{v}-\boldsymbol{v'}|r)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I_{2}(r,\boldsymbol{v})=\int_{0}^{\infty}{\rm d}v'v'\int_{0}^{\pi}{\rm d}\theta\sin\theta\int_{0}^{2\pi}{\rm d}\phi f_{a}(\boldsymbol{v}-\boldsymbol{v'}|r)
\]

\end_inset

where we need to compute the radial and tangential components of the vector
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v_{a}}=\boldsymbol{v}-\boldsymbol{v'}$
\end_inset

.
 This is where we need to make sure that the choice of convention for 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{r}$
\end_inset

 doesn't change the overall result.
 The radial component is quite straightforward since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{ar}=(\boldsymbol{v}-\boldsymbol{v'})_{r}=v_{r}-v_{r}'=v_{r}-v'\cos\theta.
\]

\end_inset

On the other hand, the tangential component is a bit more tricky.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}=(v,\theta_{0},0)$
\end_inset

 , where 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{r}=v\cos\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{t}=v\sin\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v'}=(v',\theta,\phi)$
\end_inset

.
 In cartesian coordinates, setting 
\begin_inset Formula $(Ox)=\boldsymbol{v_{t}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $(Oz)=\boldsymbol{v_{r}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(Oy)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(Oxyz)$
\end_inset

 is a direction orthonormal coordinate system, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{x}=v_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{y}=0
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{z}=v_{r}
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v'_{x}=v'\sin\theta\cos\phi
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v'_{y}=v'\sin\theta\sin\phi
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v'_{z}=v'\cos\theta
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{ax}=v_{t}-v'\sin\theta\cos\phi
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{ay}=-v'\sin\theta\sin\phi
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{az}=v_{r}-v'\cos\theta
\]

\end_inset

Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{at}^{2}=v_{ax}^{2}+v_{ay}^{2}=(v_{t}-v'\sin\theta\cos\phi)^{2}+(v'\sin\theta\sin\phi)^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{at}^{2}=v_{t}^{2}+v'^{2}\sin^{2}\theta\cos^{2}\phi-2v_{r}v'\sin\theta\cos\phi+v'^{2}\sin^{2}\theta\sin^{2}\phi
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{at}^{2}=v_{t}^{2}+v'^{2}\sin^{2}\theta-2v_{t}v'\sin\theta\cos\phi
\]

\end_inset

The complete norm of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v_{a}}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{a}^{2}=v_{ar}^{2}+v_{at}^{2}=(v_{r}-v'\cos\theta)^{2}+v_{t}^{2}+v'^{2}\sin^{2}\theta-2v_{t}v'\sin\theta\cos\phi
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{a}^{2}=v_{r}^{2}+v'^{2}\cos^{2}\theta-2v_{r}v'\cos\theta+v_{t}^{2}+v'^{2}\sin^{2}\theta-2v_{t}v'\sin\theta\cos\phi
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{a}^{2}=v^{2}+v'^{2}-2v'(v_{r}\cos\theta+v_{t}\sin\theta\cos\phi)
\]

\end_inset

which gives the binding energy per unit mass 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E(v',\theta,\phi|r)=\psi(r)-\frac{1}{2}\left[v^{2}+v'^{2}-2v'(v_{r}\cos\theta+v_{t}\sin\theta\cos\phi)\right]
\]

\end_inset

and the angular momentum per unit mass
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L(v_{ar},v_{at}|r)=r(v_{t}^{2}+v'^{2}\sin^{2}\theta-2v_{t}v'\sin\theta\cos\phi)
\]

\end_inset

Now, remember that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v_{+}}=(|v_{r}|,\boldsymbol{v_{t}})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v_{-}}=(-|v_{r}|,\boldsymbol{v_{t}})$
\end_inset

 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $+$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-$
\end_inset

 convention.
 For a given 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v'}=(v',\theta,\phi)$
\end_inset

, the angular momentum doesn't depend on the convention we chose since only
 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{r}$
\end_inset

 is impacted.
 On the other hand, for the bunding energy per unit mass, we obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{+}(v',\theta,\phi|r)=\psi(r)-\frac{1}{2}\left[v^{2}+v'^{2}-2v'(|v_{r}|\cos\theta+v_{t}\sin\theta\cos\phi)\right]
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{-}(v',\theta,\phi|r)=\psi(r)-\frac{1}{2}\left[v^{2}+v'^{2}-2v'(-|v_{r}|\cos\theta+v_{t}\sin\theta\cos\phi)\right]
\]

\end_inset

which are different.
 However, when considering 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\tilde{v}'}=(v',\pi-\theta,\phi)$
\end_inset

, which is another vector used in the integration, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{+}(v',\pi-\theta,\phi|r)=\psi(r)-\frac{1}{2}\left[v^{2}+v'^{2}-2v'(-|v_{r}|\cos\theta+v_{t}\sin\theta\cos\phi)\right]
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{-}(v',\pi-\theta,\phi|r)=\psi(r)-\frac{1}{2}\left[v^{2}+v'^{2}-2v'(|v_{r}|\cos\theta+v_{t}\sin\theta\cos\phi)\right]
\]

\end_inset

meaning that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{+}(v',\theta,\phi|r)=E_{-}(v',\pi-\theta,\phi|r)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{-}(v',\theta,\phi|r)=E_{+}(v',\pi-\theta,\phi|r)
\]

\end_inset

Furthermore, the prefactor in the integrand 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin\theta$
\end_inset

 becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin(\pi-\theta)=\sin\theta$
\end_inset

 through this transformation.
 Therefore, the convention doesn't change the result of the overall integration,
 and we may chose to set 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{r}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\in[0,\pi]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\in[0,2\pi]$
\end_inset

, and consider
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(v',\theta,\phi|r)=v^{2}+v'^{2}-2v'(v_{r}\cos\theta+v_{t}\sin\theta\cos\phi)
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $g(v',\theta,\phi|r)\geq v^{2}+v'^{2}-2v'(v_{t}+|v_{r}|)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta,\phi$
\end_inset

 in range, meaning that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(v',\theta,\phi|r)\rightarrow+\infty$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $v'\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 uniformely in angles.
 Therefore, there exists an bound 
\begin_inset Formula $v'_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\forall v'>v'_{{\rm max}},\forall\theta\in[0,\pi],\forall\phi\in[0,2\pi];g(v',\theta,\phi|r)>2\psi(r)
\]

\end_inset

that is,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\forall v'>v'_{{\rm max}},\forall\theta\in[0,\pi],\forall\phi\in[0,2\pi];E(v',\theta,\phi|r)<0
\]

\end_inset

Above this bound, as the binding energy par unit mass is negative, the DF
 of the field stars, evaluated for 
\begin_inset Formula $(v',\theta,\phi|r)$
\end_inset

, vanishes.
 This shows that the 
\begin_inset Formula $v'$
\end_inset

-integral is in fact finite.
 We can obtain this bound by solving the inequation in 
\begin_inset Formula $v'$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E(v',\theta,\phi|r)<0\Leftrightarrow v'^{2}-2v'(v_{t}+|v_{r}|)+v^{2}-2\psi(r)>0
\]

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Formula $v'$
\end_inset

 which satisfy this inequation are those which yields 
\begin_inset Formula $E(v',\theta,\phi|r)<0$
\end_inset

 (for any angle), hence a vanishing DF.
 Since the polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $v'$
\end_inset

 has non-negative leading coefficient (it is monic), the polynomial is either
 always non-negative (negative discriminant) or there is an closed interval
 over which it is negative (non-negative discriminant).
 The polynomial's discriminant is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta_{v}=4(v_{t}+|v_{r}|)^{2}-4(v^{2}-2\psi(r))=4(v_{t}^{2}+v_{r}^{2}+2|v_{r}|v_{t})-4(v^{2}-2\psi(r))=8(|v_{r}|v_{t}+\psi(r))
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $|v_{r}|,v_{t}\geq0$
\end_inset

, it is non-negative.
 In that case, the 
\begin_inset Formula $v'$
\end_inset

 over which we can integrate are those which are positive 
\begin_inset Formula $(v'\geq0)$
\end_inset

 and between the roots of the polynomial, given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v'_{\pm}=\frac{2(v_{t}+|v_{r}|)\pm\sqrt{8(|v_{r}|v_{t}+\psi(r))}}{2}=(v_{t}+|v_{r}|)\pm\sqrt{2(|v_{r}|v_{t}+\psi(r))}.
\]

\end_inset

One may ask if 
\begin_inset Formula $v'_{-}$
\end_inset

 is positive or negative.
 To that, recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $|v_{r}|=v\cos\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{t}=v\sin\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{0}\in[0,\pi/2]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v'_{-}=v(\cos\theta+\sin\theta)-\sqrt{2(v^{2}\cos\theta\sin\theta+\psi(r))}
\]

\end_inset

We have that 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{-}\leq0$
\end_inset

 iif 
\begin_inset Formula $v(\cos\theta_{0}+\sin\theta_{0})\leq\sqrt{2(v^{2}\cos\theta_{0}\sin\theta_{0}+\psi(r))}$
\end_inset

.
 Both sides are positive for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{0}\in[0,\pi/2]$
\end_inset

, therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{-}\leq0$
\end_inset

 iif 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v^{2}(\cos\theta_{0}+\sin\theta_{0})^{2}\leq2(v^{2}\cos\theta_{0}\sin\theta_{0}+\psi(r))
\]

\end_inset

iff 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{2}(1+2\cos\theta_{0}\sin\theta_{0})\leq2(v^{2}\cos\theta_{0}\sin\theta_{0}+\psi(r))$
\end_inset

 iff 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{2}\leq2\psi(r)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $E=\psi(r)-\frac{1}{2}v^{2}$
\end_inset

, this is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $2(\psi(r)-E)\leq2\psi(r)$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $E\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, since we study systems with 
\begin_inset Formula $E\geq0$
\end_inset

, it follows that we always have 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{-}\leq0$
\end_inset

, meaning that our integration is over 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,v'_{+}]$
\end_inset

.
 This upper bound depends on 
\begin_inset Formula $E,L,r$
\end_inset

 and is given by the formula as long as 
\begin_inset Formula $E\leq\psi(r)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L\leq r\sqrt{2(\psi(r)-E)}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{+}=\left(\frac{L}{r}+\sqrt{2(\psi(r)-E)-\frac{L^{2}}{r^{2}}}\right)+\sqrt{2\left(\frac{L}{r}\sqrt{2(\psi(r)-E)-\frac{L^{2}}{r^{2}}}+\psi(r)\right)}
\]

\end_inset

This condition will always be satisfied in a star orbit (see next section).
 It can be useful to define the effective binding potential
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi_{{\rm eff}}(r;L)=\psi(r)-\frac{L^{2}}{2r^{2}},
\]

\end_inset

so that we can rewrite the upper bound of the integral as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{{\rm max}}=\frac{L}{r}+\sqrt{2(\psi_{{\rm eff}}(r;L)-E)}+\sqrt{2\left(\frac{L}{r}\sqrt{2(\psi_{{\rm eff}}(r;L)-E)}+\psi(r)\right)}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K(v'|r)=\int_{0}^{\pi}{\rm d}\theta\sin\theta\int_{0}^{2\pi}{\rm d}\phi f_{a}\left(\begin{array}{ccl}
v_{ar} & = & v_{r}-v'\cos\theta\\
v_{at} & = & v_{t}^{2}+v'^{2}\sin^{2}\theta-2v_{t}v'\sin\theta\cos\phi
\end{array}\bigg|r\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{a}(v_{ar},v_{at}|r)=F_{q}(E(v_{ar},v_{at}|r),L(v_{ar},v_{at}|r))
\]

\end_inset

with
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E(v_{ar},v_{at}|r)=\psi(r)-\frac{1}{2}\left[v^{2}+v'^{2}-2v'(v_{r}\cos\theta+v_{t}\sin\theta\cos\phi)\right]
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L(v_{ar},v_{at}|r)=r(v_{t}^{2}+v'^{2}\sin^{2}\theta-2v_{t}v'\sin\theta\cos\phi)
\]

\end_inset

With the change of variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\cos\theta$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K(v'|r)=\int_{-1}^{1}{\rm d}x\int_{0}^{2\pi}{\rm d}\phi f_{a}\left(\begin{array}{ccl}
v_{ar} & = & v_{r}-v'x\\
v_{at} & = & \sqrt{v_{t}^{2}+v'^{2}(1-x^{2})-2v_{t}v'\sqrt{1-x^{2}}\cos\phi}
\end{array}\bigg|r\right)
\]

\end_inset

with
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E(v_{ar},v_{at}|r)=\psi(r)-\frac{1}{2}\left[v^{2}+v'^{2}-2v'(v_{r}x+v_{t}\sqrt{1-x^{2}}\cos\phi)\right]
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L(v_{ar},v_{at}|r)=r(v_{t}^{2}+v'^{2}(1-x^{2})-2v_{t}v'\sqrt{1-x^{2}}\cos\phi)
\]

\end_inset

Double integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $[-1,1]\times[0,2\pi]$
\end_inset

.
 Use the function hcubature from the package HCubature (https://github.com/JuliaM
ath/HCubature.jl).
 Maybe even do 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,v'_{{\rm max}}]\times[-1,1]\times[0,2\pi]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, switch to 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,L)$
\end_inset

 space and using eq.
 (C15) to (C19) of Bar-Or & Alexander (2016), which doesn't rely on an isotropy
 assumption, we obtain (evaluate at 
\begin_inset Formula $(r,\boldsymbol{v}(E,L))$
\end_inset

) at first order in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta v/v$
\end_inset

 (with opposite convention for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta v_{||}$
\end_inset

, as we defined 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\boldsymbol{v}=\boldsymbol{v'}-\boldsymbol{v}=-\Delta v_{||}\hat{\boldsymbol{v}}+\Delta\boldsymbol{v_{\perp}}$
\end_inset

) :
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle\Delta E\rangle(r,E,L)=v\langle\Delta v_{||}\rangle-\frac{1}{2}\langle(\Delta v_{||})^{2}\rangle-\frac{1}{2}\langle(\Delta v_{\perp})^{2}\rangle
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle(\Delta E)^{2}\rangle(r,E,L)=v^{2}\langle(\Delta v_{||})^{2}\rangle
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle\Delta L\rangle(r,E,L)=-\frac{L}{v}\langle\Delta v_{||}\rangle+\frac{r^{2}}{4L}\langle(\Delta v_{\perp})^{2}\rangle
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle(\Delta L)^{2}\rangle(r,E,L)=\frac{L^{2}}{v^{2}}\langle(\Delta v_{||})^{2}\rangle+\frac{1}{2}\left(r^{2}-\frac{L^{2}}{v^{2}}\right)\langle(\Delta v_{\perp})^{2}\rangle
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle\Delta E\Delta L\rangle(r,E,L)=-L\langle(\Delta v_{||})^{2}\rangle
\]

\end_inset

Finally, due to our analysis, those quantities are well defined and we can
 use the bijective transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,L|r)\leftrightarrow(v_{r},v_{t}|r)$
\end_inset

, , through the relations
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E(v_{r},v_{t}|r)=\psi(r)-\frac{1}{2}v_{r}{}^{2}-\frac{1}{2}v_{t}{}^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L(v_{r},v_{t}|r)=rv_{t}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{r},v_{t}\geq0$
\end_inset

, yielding 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in]-\infty,\psi(r)]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L\in[0,r\sqrt{2(\psi(r)-E)}]$
\end_inset

, while the converse relations are
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{t}(E,L|r)=\frac{L}{r}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{r}(E,L|r)=\sqrt{2(\psi_{{\rm eff}}(r;L)-E)}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in]-\infty,\psi(r)]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L\in[0,r\sqrt{2(\psi(r)-E)}]$
\end_inset

, yielding 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{r},v_{t}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Orbit of a test star in a globular cluster
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can now compute the local diffusion coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\Delta E\rangle(r,E,L)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle(\Delta E)^{2}\rangle(r,E,L)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\Delta L\rangle(r,E,L)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle(\Delta L)^{2}\rangle(r,E,L)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\Delta E\Delta L\rangle(r,E,L)$
\end_inset

.
 Since we are interested in the secular evolution of the system, we can
 average over the dynamical time and smear out the star along its orbit.
 This leads us to consider the orbit-average diffusion coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{D_{X}}(E,L)\doteqdot\langle D_{X}\rangle_{\leftturn}(E,L)=\frac{1}{T}\int_{0}^{T}\langle\Delta X\rangle(r(t),E,L){\rm d}t=\frac{2}{T}\int_{r_{min}}^{r_{max}}\langle\Delta X\rangle(r,E,L)\frac{{\rm d}r}{v_{r}(r,E,L)}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{D_{XY}}(E,L)\doteqdot\langle D_{XY}\rangle_{\leftturn}(E,L)=\frac{1}{T}\int_{0}^{T}\langle\Delta X\Delta Y\rangle(r(t),E,L){\rm d}t=\frac{2}{T}\int_{r_{min}}^{r_{max}}\langle\Delta X\Delta Y\rangle(r,E,L)\frac{{\rm d}r}{v_{r}(r,E,L)}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{r}(r)$
\end_inset

 is the radial velocity of the orbiting star at 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 However, this suppose that the star follow 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

nice
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 trajectories.
 This is what we will look into in this section.
 Furthermore, since 
\begin_inset Formula $E,L$
\end_inset

 are chosen so that the trajectory is a circular orbit with radius 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, then we apply the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

time
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 formula instead of the radial velocity one and obtain 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{D_{X}}(E,L)=\frac{1}{T}\int_{0}^{T}\langle\Delta X\rangle(R,E,L){\rm d}t=\langle\Delta X\rangle(R,E,L)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{D_{XY}}(E,L)=\frac{1}{T}\int_{0}^{T}\langle\Delta X\Delta Y\rangle(R,E,L){\rm d}t=\langle\Delta X\Delta Y\rangle(R,E,L)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Study of an orbit
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
-> See Kurth (1955), Astronomische Nachrichten, volume 282, Issue 6, p.241.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a test star described by its position vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}$
\end_inset

, its binding energye (opposite of its energy) 
\begin_inset Formula $E(t)$
\end_inset

 and its angular momentum vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{L}(t)$
\end_inset

, per unit mass.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E(t)=\psi(r(t))-\frac{1}{2}\boldsymbol{\dot{r}}^{2}(t)=\psi(r(t))-\frac{1}{2}\dot{r}^{2}(t)-\frac{1}{2}r^{2}(t)\dot{\theta}^{2}(t)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{L}(t)=\boldsymbol{r}(t)\times\boldsymbol{v}(t)
\]

\end_inset

Differentiating the binding energy and using Newton's law shows that it
 is conserved.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E(t)=E$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, differentiating 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{L}(t)$
\end_inset

 and using the fact that the potential is central shows that this quantity
 is also conserved.
 Therefore the star's orbit is kept within a fixed plane determined by its
 initial conditions.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $L(t)=L$
\end_inset

 be its conserved norm.
 We also have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L=r(t)v_{t}(t)=r(t)^{2}\dot{\theta}(t)
\]

\end_inset

In our case, consider an orbit with binding energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E\geq0$
\end_inset

 and angular momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $L\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 We can rewriting the energy conservation equation (on one orbit) as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E=\psi(r)-\frac{1}{2}\dot{r}^{2}-\frac{L^{2}}{2r^{2}}\Leftrightarrow\dot{r}^{2}=2(\psi(r)-E)-\frac{L^{2}}{r^{2}}=2(\psi_{{\rm eff}}(r;L)-E)
\]

\end_inset

Define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{r}(r)\doteqdot\sqrt{2(\psi_{{\rm eff}}(r;L)-E)}\geq0
\]

\end_inset

Consider starting the motion from a radius with position initial radial
 velocity.
 Then as long as the radial velocity is positive, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{t}\frac{\dot{r}(t){\rm d}t}{v_{r}(r(t))}=t\Leftrightarrow\int_{r_{{\rm min}}}^{r(t)}\frac{{\rm d}r}{v_{r}(r)}=t.
\]

\end_inset

This motion goes on until 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{r}(\tau)=0$
\end_inset

 for some time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau=\int_{r_{{\rm min}}}^{r_{\max}}\frac{{\rm d}r}{v_{r}(r)}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\max}$
\end_inset

 is the radius reached at 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 Then the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ddot{r}$
\end_inset

 (negative) decreases 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 until a radius 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{{\rm min}}$
\end_inset

 which has vanishing radial velocity (but positive 
\begin_inset Formula $\ddot{r}$
\end_inset

), and the process repeats itself (see next section for a proof of those
 accelerations).
 Note that the motion from 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\max}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\min}$
\end_inset

 is symmetrical to that from 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\min}$
\end_inset

to 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\max}$
\end_inset

, as it follows the relation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{\tau}^{t}\frac{\dot{r}(t){\rm d}t}{-v_{r}(r(t))}=t-\tau\Leftrightarrow\int_{r_{{\rm max}}}^{r(t)}\frac{{\rm d}r}{v_{r}(r)}=\tau-t
\]

\end_inset

hence
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{r_{{\rm min}}}^{r(t)}\frac{{\rm d}r}{v_{r}(r)}-\int_{r_{{\rm min}}}^{r_{\max}}\frac{{\rm d}r}{v_{r}(r)}=\tau-t\Leftrightarrow\int_{r_{{\rm min}}}^{r(t)}\frac{{\rm d}r}{v_{r}(r)}=2\tau-t.
\]

\end_inset

Letting the orbit start at 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\min}$
\end_inset

 and setting 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F(r)=\int_{r_{\min}}^{r}\frac{dx}{v_{r}(x)},
\]

\end_inset

we obtain an expression for the radius of the orbit
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r(t)=\begin{cases}
F^{-1}(t) & t\in[0,\tau]\\
F^{-1}(2\tau-t) & t\in[\tau,2\tau]
\end{cases},
\]

\end_inset

with the symmetry 
\begin_inset Formula $r(t)=r(2\tau-t)$
\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Formula $2\tau$
\end_inset

-periodicity of the radius.
 Furthermore, notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $1/v_{r}(r)$
\end_inset

 is integrable at 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\min}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\max}$
\end_inset

.
 To show this, consider what happens near 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\max}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{r}^{2}(r_{\max}-\epsilon)=2(\psi(r_{\max}-\epsilon)-E)-\frac{L^{2}}{(r_{\max}-\epsilon)^{2}}=2(\psi(r_{\max})-\psi'(r_{\max})\epsilon+o(\epsilon)-E)-\frac{L^{2}}{r_{\max}^{2}}\frac{1}{(1-\frac{\epsilon}{r_{\max}})^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{r}^{2}(r_{\max}-\epsilon)=2(\psi(r_{\max})-\psi'(r_{\max})\epsilon+o(\epsilon)-E)-\frac{L^{2}}{r_{\max}^{2}}(1+\frac{2\epsilon}{r_{\max}}+o(\epsilon))
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{r}^{2}(r_{\max}-\epsilon)=\underbrace{v_{r}^{2}(r_{\max})}_{=0}-2\psi'(r_{\max})\epsilon-\frac{2L^{2}\epsilon}{r_{\max}^{3}}+o(\epsilon)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{r}^{2}(r_{\max}-\epsilon)=\frac{2r_{\max}}{(1+r_{\max}^{2})^{3/2}}\epsilon-\frac{2L^{2}\epsilon}{r_{\max}^{3}}+o(\epsilon)
\]

\end_inset

Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{v_{r}(r_{\max}-\epsilon)}=\left(\underbrace{\frac{2r_{\max}}{(1+r_{\max}^{2})^{3/2}}-\frac{2L^{2}}{r_{\max}^{3}}}_{=-2\psi_{{\rm eff}}'(r_{\max})\geq0}\right)^{-1/2}\frac{1}{\sqrt{\epsilon}}(1+o(1))
\]

\end_inset

A similar calculation yields
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{v_{r}(r_{\min}+\epsilon)}=\left(\underbrace{-\frac{2r_{\min}}{(1+r_{\min}^{2})^{3/2}}+\frac{2L^{2}}{r_{\min}^{3}}}_{=2\psi_{{\rm eff}}'(r_{\min})\geq0}\right)^{-1/2}\frac{1}{\sqrt{\epsilon}}(1+o(1))
\]

\end_inset

which is integrable since 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\sqrt{\epsilon}$
\end_inset

 is integrable at 
\begin_inset Formula $0^{+}$
\end_inset

 if the 
\begin_inset Formula $()^{-1/2}$
\end_inset

 term in strictly positive.
 Once we have shown this, we can conclude that the orbit is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

rosette-like
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, with periodical radius of periode 
\begin_inset Formula $T=2\tau$
\end_inset

 with
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau=\int_{r_{{\rm min}}}^{r_{\max}}\frac{{\rm d}r}{v_{r}(r)}.
\]

\end_inset

Note that given an uncertainty 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta r$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\min},r_{\max}$
\end_inset

, because of the 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\sqrt{\epsilon}$
\end_inset

 uncertaintly on the edges, the uncertainty on 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is about 
\begin_inset Formula $(2|\psi_{{\rm eff}}'(r_{\min}))^{-1/2}|\sqrt{2\delta r_{\min}},(2|\psi_{{\rm eff}}'(r_{\max})|^{-1/2}\sqrt{2\delta r_{\max}}$
\end_inset

.
 Because we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta\psi_{{\rm eff}}(r_{\min})\simeq|\psi_{{\rm eff}}'(r_{\min})|\delta r_{\min};\quad\delta\psi_{{\rm eff}}(r_{\max})\simeq|\psi_{{\rm eff}}'(r_{\max})|\delta r_{\max},
\]

\end_inset

it follows that the period uncertainty is about
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta\tau\simeq(2|\psi_{{\rm eff}}(r_{\min}))^{-1/2}|\sqrt{2\frac{\delta\psi_{{\rm eff}}(r_{\min})}{|\psi_{{\rm eff}}'(r_{\min})|}}+(2|\psi_{{\rm eff}}(r_{\max})|^{-1/2}\sqrt{2\frac{\delta\psi_{{\rm eff}}(r_{\max})}{|\psi_{{\rm eff}}'(r_{\max})|}}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta\tau\simeq\frac{\sqrt{\delta\psi_{{\rm eff}}(r_{\min})}}{|\psi_{{\rm eff}}'(r_{\min})|}+\frac{\sqrt{\delta\psi_{{\rm eff}}(r_{\max})}}{|\psi_{{\rm eff}}'(r_{\max})|}
\]

\end_inset

For example, for 
\begin_inset Formula $E=L=0.1$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{\min}=0.074651;\quad r_{\max}9.944796,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta\psi_{{\rm eff}}(r_{\min})=2.704246\cdot10^{-9};\quad\delta\psi_{{\rm eff}}(r_{\max})=0
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|\psi_{{\rm eff}}'(r_{\min})|=23.963907;\quad|\psi_{{\rm eff}}'(r_{\max})|=9.949719\cdot10^{-3}
\]

\end_inset

hence
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta\tau=1.062293\cdot10^{-5}
\]

\end_inset

where the computed period with quadgk is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau=5.108382.
\]

\end_inset

 As for the angle, its derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\theta}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

-periodical since 
\begin_inset Formula $L=r^{2}\dot{\theta}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $r\geq0$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

-periodical.
 Therefore it can be decomposed as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\theta(t)=\omega t+p(t)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p(t)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

-periodical and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is a real constant.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=\frac{1}{T}\int_{0}^{T}\dot{\theta}(t){\rm d}t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p(t)=\theta(t)-\omega t$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(t+T)=\theta(t+T)-\omega(t+T)=\int_{0}^{t}\dot{\theta}(t){\rm d}t+\int_{t}^{t+T}\dot{\theta}(t){\rm d}t-\omega t-\omega T
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(t+T)=\left(\int_{0}^{t}\dot{\theta}(t){\rm d}t-\omega t\right)+\left(\int_{0}^{T}\dot{\theta}(t){\rm d}t-\int_{0}^{T}\dot{\theta}(t){\rm d}t\right)=(\theta(t)-\omega t)=p(t)
\]

\end_inset

showing that 
\begin_inset Formula $p(t)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

-periodical.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, to find what 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\min}$
\end_inset

 are, we need to solve 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{r}(r)=0$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(r)-E-\frac{L^{2}}{2r^{2}}=0$
\end_inset

, i.e.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+r^{2}}}=\frac{L^{2}}{2r^{2}}+E=\frac{2Er^{2}+L^{2}}{2r^{2}}\Leftrightarrow\frac{1}{1+r^{2}}=\frac{(2Er^{2}+L^{2})^{2}}{4r^{4}}\Leftrightarrow4r^{4}=(2Er^{2}+L^{2})^{2}(1+r^{2})
\]

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=r^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
4X^{2}=(2EX+L^{2})^{2}(1+X)\Leftrightarrow4E^{2}X^{3}+4(E^{2}-1+EL^{2})X^{2}+(4EL^{2}+L^{4})X+L^{4}=0
\]

\end_inset

This is a degree-3 polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 It has 3 real roots iff its discriminant 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 is strictly positive (two real roots, one of which is double, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=0$
\end_inset

).
 Let
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha=4E^{2};\quad\beta=4(E^{2}-1+EL^{2});\quad\gamma=4EL^{2}+L^{4};\quad\delta=L^{4}.
\]

\end_inset

Then the polynomial has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha X^{3}+\beta X^{2}+\gamma X+\delta$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $E>0$
\end_inset

.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X=Y-\frac{\beta}{3\alpha};\quad p=\frac{3\alpha\gamma-\beta^{2}}{3\alpha^{2}};\quad q=\frac{2\beta^{3}-9\alpha\beta\gamma+27\alpha^{2}\delta}{27\alpha^{3}},
\]

\end_inset

we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha X^{3}+\beta X^{2}+\gamma X+\delta=0$
\end_inset

 iff 
\begin_inset Formula $Y^{3}+pY+q=0$
\end_inset

 where the roots of the two polynomials are linked by the formula 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}=Y_{i}-\frac{\beta}{3\alpha}.$
\end_inset

 As for the discriminant of the 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 polynomial, it is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta=-(4p^{3}+27q^{2}).
\]

\end_inset

Since only its sign matter on looking for the behavior of the solutions,
 we may only compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta<0$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $4p^{3}+27q^{2}>0$
\end_inset

, then the polynomial has only one real root given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y=\left(-\frac{q}{2}+\sqrt{\frac{q^{2}}{4}+\frac{p^{3}}{27}}\right)^{1/3}+\left(-\frac{q}{2}-\sqrt{\frac{q^{2}}{4}+\frac{p^{3}}{27}}\right)^{1/3}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\geq0$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $4p^{3}+27q^{2}\geq0$
\end_inset

, then there are three real roots given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y_{k}=2\sqrt{-\frac{p}{3}}\cos\left[\frac{1}{3}\arccos\left(\frac{3q}{2p}\sqrt{-\frac{3}{p}}\right)-\frac{2\pi k}{3}\right],\quad k\in\{0,1,2\}.
\]

\end_inset

Note that when 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=0$
\end_inset

, this reduces to the two roots 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y_{0}=2\sqrt{-\frac{p}{3}},\quad Y_{1,2}=-\sqrt{-\frac{p}{3}}.
\]

\end_inset

 Recall 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{r}^{2}/2=\psi_{{\rm eff}}(r;L)-E$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\geq0$
\end_inset

 on the orbit).
 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{{\rm eff}}(r;L)$
\end_inset

 has derivative is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi'_{{\rm eff}}(r;L)=\frac{L^{2}}{r^{3}}-\frac{r}{(1+r^{2})^{3/2}}
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi'_{{\rm eff}}(r;L)\leq0$
\end_inset

 iif 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{4}/L^{2}\geq(1+r^{2})^{3/2}$
\end_inset

.
 Left term grows more quickly 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sim r^{4})$
\end_inset

 that the second term 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sim r^{3})$
\end_inset

 but stars at 0 whereas second term starts at 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2>0$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore the two curves cross at a unique point, and this inequality is
 satisfied after this point.
 This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{{\rm eff}}(r;L)$
\end_inset

 is increasing until some point, then decreases.
 In this maximum is stricly below 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, then there are no solution.
 If the maximum is exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, then there is only one solution and the orbit is circular.
 If the maximum is strictly above 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, then they are two solutions which are 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{{\rm min}}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\max}$
\end_inset

.
 The latter is because 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{r\rightarrow\infty}\psi_{{\rm eff}}(r;L)=0<E$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we are in the case of no solution, then 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{r}(r)=2(\psi_{{\rm eff}}(r;L)-E)<0$
\end_inset

, which is impossible on an orbit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we are in the case with two solutions, then the solution are not the
 maximum of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{{\rm eff}}(r;L)$
\end_inset

, meaning that the derivative evaluated at the solutions are non-zero.
 This completes the proof that 
\begin_inset Formula $1/v_{r}(r)$
\end_inset

 is integrable at 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\max}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\min}$
\end_inset

 as the integral of 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\sqrt{r-r_{{\rm m}}}$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{{\rm eff}}(r;L)$
\end_inset

 must have two positive distincts solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\min},r_{\max}$
\end_inset

, then the polynomial should also have two distincts positive solutions
 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{{\rm max}}=r_{\max}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\min}=r_{\min}^{2}$
\end_inset

 (and the third one being negative).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One should check whether a given couple 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,L)$
\end_inset

 allows for bound orbits.
 That that end, we should find if there exists at least one 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 that that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{{\rm eff}}(r;L)\geq E$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 if there are solution to the polynomial.
 Equivalently, this reduces to computing the discriminant 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 and testing if it is positive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Computing the binding energy of a circular orbit given 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have now access to the NR, orbit-averaged diffusion coefficients in 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,L)$
\end_inset

-space for the allowed bound orbits: 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{D}_{E}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{D}_{EE}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{D}_{L}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{D}_{LL}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{D}_{EL}$
\end_inset

, functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,L)$
\end_inset

.
 The allowed region in 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,L)$
\end_inset

 space is composed of the 
\begin_inset Formula $E,L\geq0$
\end_inset

 such that there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $r>0$
\end_inset

 verifying the inequality 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{{\rm eff}}(r;L)\geq E$
\end_inset

, where we defined the effective potential
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi_{{\rm eff}}(r;L)=\psi(r)-\frac{L^{2}}{2r^{2}}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+r^{2}}}-\frac{L^{2}}{2r^{2}}.
\]

\end_inset

As shown before, for 
\begin_inset Formula $L>0$
\end_inset

, this function has limits 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{0}\psi_{{\rm eff}}=-\infty$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{+\infty}\psi_{{\rm eff}}=0$
\end_inset

, is increasing until a global maximum before decreasing towards 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 Raising the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 lowers this maximum value, meaning that there exists a value 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{{\rm c}}(E)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{{\rm eff}}(r;L_{c}(E))=E$
\end_inset

.
 Then, the forbidden angular momenta (for a given 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

) are the 
\begin_inset Formula $L>L_{{\rm c}}(E)$
\end_inset

.
 Due to the discussion in the previous section, this couple 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,L_{{\rm c}}(E))$
\end_inset

 determines a circular orbit.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are a priori no analytical formula composed only of basic operations
 and radical for 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{{\rm c}}(E)$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, we noted that an orbit with 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,L)$
\end_inset

 was circular if the discriminant 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=18\alpha\beta\gamma\delta-4\beta^{3}\delta+\beta^{2}\gamma^{2}-4\alpha\gamma^{3}-27\alpha^{2}\delta^{2}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=4E^{2};\beta=4(E^{2}-1+EL^{2});\gamma=4EL^{2}+L^{4};\delta=L^{4}$
\end_inset

, was zero.
 This is a degree-6 polynomial equation in the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}$
\end_inset

, which has no such formula for its solutions (Abel, 1826).
 However, we may approximate it.
 For simplicity's sake, look for 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{c}(L)$
\end_inset

 at a given 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 It is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{c}(L)=\max_{r>0}\psi_{{\rm eff}}(r;L)=\psi_{{\rm eff}}(r_{*}^{L};L)$
\end_inset

.
 To approximate this 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{*}^{L}$
\end_inset

, we may look for it using Newton's method applied to 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi'_{{\rm eff}}$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi'_{{\rm eff}}(r_{*}^{L};L)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Start at 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{0}^{L}=L^{2/3}$
\end_inset

 , where the evaluation yields
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi'_{{\rm eff}}(L^{2/3};L)=1-\frac{L^{2/3}}{(1+L^{4/3})^{3/2}}\in[1-\sqrt{4/27},1]\simeq[0.615,1]
\]

\end_inset

in order not to be too far away from 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi'_{{\rm eff}}(r_{*}^{L};L)=0$
\end_inset

, and apply the recursion
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{n+1}^{L}=r_{n}^{L}-\frac{\psi'_{{\rm eff}}(r_{n};L)}{\psi''_{{\rm eff}}(r_{n};L)},
\]

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi'_{{\rm eff}}(r;L)=-\frac{r}{(1+r^{2})^{3/2}}+\frac{L^{2}}{r^{3}};\quad\psi''_{{\rm eff}}(r_{n};L)=-\frac{(1+r^{2})^{3/2}-3r^{2}\sqrt{1+r^{2}}}{(1+r^{2})^{3}}-3\frac{L^{2}}{r^{4}}.
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{n}^{L}\rightarrow r_{*}^{L}$
\end_inset

.
 We can show that 
\begin_inset Formula $(r_{n}^{L})$
\end_inset

 is increasing since 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi'_{{\rm eff}}(r_{n}^{L};L)>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi''_{{\rm eff}}(r_{n}^{L};L)<0$
\end_inset

 (and convexity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi'_{{\rm eff}}$
\end_inset

 where it matters).
 Therefore a good stopping condition is to get the lowest 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi'_{{\rm eff}}(r_{N}^{L}+\epsilon)<0$
\end_inset

 for some precision 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

.
 Then, taking 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{r}_{*}^{L}=(r_{N}^{L}+r_{N}^{L}+\epsilon)/2=r_{N}^{L}+\epsilon/2$
\end_inset

 we will have 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{{\rm c}}(L)\simeq\psi_{{\rm eff}}(\tilde{r}_{*}^{L};L)$
\end_inset

, with precision 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta E_{{\rm c}}(L)\simeq|\psi_{{\rm eff}}(r_{*}^{L};L)-\psi_{{\rm eff}}(\tilde{r}_{*}^{L};L)|\simeq\frac{1}{2}|\underbrace{\psi_{{\rm eff}}^{(2)}(r_{*}^{L})}_{<0}|\cdot|r_{*}^{L}-\tilde{r}_{*}^{L}|^{2}\simeq|\psi_{{\rm eff}}^{(2)}(r_{*}^{L})|\frac{\epsilon^{2}}{8}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Study of the radiux acceleration 
\begin_inset Formula $\ddot{r}$
\end_inset

 for non-circular orbits
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A condition to the periodicity of 
\begin_inset Formula $r(t)$
\end_inset

 is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ddot{r}(t)$
\end_inset

 should be strictly negative when reaching 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\max}$
\end_inset

 and strictly positive when reaching 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\min}$
\end_inset

, so that for small 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

 (time just after 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{\max}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{\min}$
\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r(t_{\max}+\epsilon)=r(t_{\max})+\dot{r}(t_{\max})\epsilon+\ddot{r}(t_{\max})\frac{\epsilon^{2}}{2}+o(\epsilon^{2})=r_{\max}+\ddot{r}_{\max}\frac{\epsilon^{2}}{2}+o(\epsilon^{2})<r_{\max},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r(t_{\min}+\epsilon)=r(t_{\min})+\dot{r}(t_{\min})\epsilon+\ddot{r}(t_{\min})\frac{\epsilon^{2}}{2}+o(\epsilon^{2})=r_{\min}+\ddot{r}_{\min}\frac{\epsilon^{2}}{2}+o(\epsilon^{2})>r_{\min}.
\]

\end_inset

Newton's law asserts that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{r}=\ddot{r}-r\dot{\theta}^{2}=\psi'(r)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $L=r^{2}\dot{\theta}$
\end_inset

, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\ddot{r}=\psi'(r)+\frac{L^{2}}{r^{3}}=\psi'_{{\rm eff}}(r;L)$
\end_inset

.
 In the case of a non-circular orbits, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\max}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\min}$
\end_inset

 don't correspond to maxima of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi{}_{{\rm eff}}(r;L)$
\end_inset

, therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi'_{{\rm eff}}(r;L)$
\end_inset

 doesn't vanish at those points.
 Furthermore, we showed that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi{}_{{\rm eff}}(r;L)$
\end_inset

 was strictly increasing until its maximum, then was strictly decreasing.
 This proves that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ddot{r}_{\min}>0$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ddot{r}_{\max}<0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Diffusion equation and change of variables
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All in all, those coefficients appear in the Fokker-Planck diffusion equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial P}{\partial t}(E,L,t)=-\frac{\partial}{\partial E}\left[\bar{D}_{E}P\right]+\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial E^{2}}\left[\bar{D}_{EE}P\right]-\frac{\partial}{\partial L}\left[\bar{D}_{L}P\right]+\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial L^{2}}\left[\bar{D}_{LL}P\right]+\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial E\partial L}\left[\bar{D}_{EL}P\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we want to change coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\rightarrow\boldsymbol{x'}(\boldsymbol{x})$
\end_inset

, we may use the formulae (C.52) and (C.53) p.25 from Bar-Or & Alexander (2016)
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D'_{l}=\frac{\partial x'_{l}}{\partial x_{k}}D_{k}+\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial^{2}x'_{l}}{\partial x_{r}\partial x_{k}}D_{rk},
\]

\end_inset

(error on the sign? should be
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D'_{l}=\frac{\partial x'_{l}}{\partial x_{k}}D_{k}-\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial^{2}x'_{l}}{\partial x_{r}\partial x_{k}}D_{rk}\quad?)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D'_{lm}=\frac{\partial x'_{l}}{\partial x_{r}}\frac{\partial x'_{m}}{\partial x_{k}}D_{rk}.
\]

\end_inset

We might be interested in the change of variable 
\begin_inset Formula $(E,L)\rightarrow(E,\ell)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(E,L)=L/L_{{\rm c}}(E)$
\end_inset

.
 We have
\end_layout

